WEBVTT

00:01.930 --> 00:04.988
Nice bright day in College Station. Have the 
pleasure of chatting with Harrison Hurth, fellow

00:08.650 --> 00:18.680
Presbyterian, and a dear friend about his 
experiences here at College Station.

00:24.198 --> 00:29.556
This is February 15, 1999, a bright sunny day. Have 
the pleasure and honor of chatting with Harrison

00:30.880 --> 00:32.610
Hurth. Before we start talking about A&M so that 
anyone in the future might know a little bit about

00:37.740 --> 00:42.060
your background before A&M, give us a brief 
biographical summary of your experience before

00:42.040 --> 00:48.380
coming to College Station. Okay, well I was born in 
Pontiac, Illinois, I went to undergraduate

00:50.045 --> 01:01.480
school at Illinois Western University. I married 
her in 1938.

01:10.017 --> 01:20.039
I went then to the University of Illinois for a 
master's degree, and I taught for a number of years

01:10.017 --> 01:20.039
in Illinois high school. It's in Clintonville, 
Illinois. And I came to A&M when the University of

01:20.660 --> 01:33.930
Illinois placement office sent me a notice that 
A&M wanted some teachers for summer school. That

01:33.910 --> 01:43.760
didn't sound like a summer resort, and I thought, 
well, that's a chance to give the collegiate level

01:33.910 --> 01:43.760
a shot, so I applied. What year was that? That was 
19, and Dr. Thomas Mayo replied and said he didn't

01:44.740 --> 01:56.740
need anyone after all, but would be contacting me 
in the fall, but maybe not. Something between a

01:58.813 --> 02:03.020
possibility and a polite brush off. And I think on 
the Fourth of July weekend, I re-enlisted,

02:03.000 --> 02:14.220
and he had called me prior to that. And I talked it 
over with him, and he did make, he had made me an

02:14.200 --> 02:20.910
offer. So I called on that weekend, so they'd come a 
week late in 19, the 4th, September 19th. My

02:29.930 --> 02:35.652
younger daughter had just been, was not really 
doing too well. Margaret was still in the

02:35.792 --> 02:37.820
hospital. I came down alone, and someone had been 
covering for me. I'd be interested, you came by

02:43.390 --> 02:45.410
car? Came by car. And what, how much gear did you 
bring in that car? Well, I had a, what I had was a, I

02:50.390 --> 03:08.750
didn't have a

02:50.390 --> 03:08.750
very big truck, so I bought enough stuff to 
survive, because I had enough clothing to last

03:08.730 --> 03:12.750
until Thanksgiving. And when I got my wife, I met 
her in Memphis. And then you all drove back. Was

03:20.957 --> 03:23.720
that your only car? Yeah, what happened this time, 
we sent her mother to Memphis. I went to Memphis on

03:32.900 --> 03:40.020
the train, and we drove back there in her mother's 
car. Where were you all living then? Well, we lived

03:41.000 --> 03:44.020
out to A&M Annex. The University of New College had 
taken over the old Bryan Air Base, and turned it

03:44.000 --> 03:51.690
into the A&M Annex. And we had an apartment in what 
had been an officer's ward in the hospital. That

03:57.520 --> 03:59.237
scared me. I was going to bring a new baby down. I 
spent every evening, old

04:01.520 --> 04:10.370
Dutch cleanser, scrubbing down the wall. And we 
had a large room big enough for us. We did not use the

04:13.350 --> 04:18.730
apartment behind it. Five

04:18.710 --> 04:26.740
radiators, two or three commodes. And was this 
furnished? Yes. What kind of furniture was in it?

04:33.280 --> 04:37.715
Well, no I'm sorry, it was not furnished. That's 
another story. When

04:38.400 --> 04:52.680
the furniture truck drove up, the driver demanded 
$700, which I had a lot of money then. I didn't have

04:52.660 --> 04:54.680
something. Uh-huh. I hot-footed it into the First 
National Bank. And Dr. Jeff got $700. And I've

05:03.880 --> 05:06.900
banked with them ever since. I can imagine how that 
would be important. Air Base experience, I think,

05:12.450 --> 05:18.490
is very, very important, that story. About what 
was the enrollment out there, and the faculty. How

05:26.130 --> 05:30.030
many folks were there? 1946 was the year of the 
veterans. The enrollment of the college was

05:34.640 --> 05:40.530
virtually double the total enrollment. It must 
have been in the area of seven classes. And they put

05:43.510 --> 05:47.990
a freshman class. All freshmen? All freshmen. 
What would that

05:49.970 --> 05:56.390
mean? And some of those were veterans and some were 
not. Is that right? I'm not sure whether veterans

06:01.370 --> 06:07.774
went to the annex or not. I'm really not sure. All 
right, so you're implying that most of them were

06:09.320 --> 06:13.340
right out of high school. Most of them were 
freshmen right out of high school. We had the whole

06:16.180 --> 06:18.200
set-up. They had Harrington and John Paul Abbott 
at different

06:18.180 --> 06:35.100
times, whatever the title was. I believe they 
called them deans and directed the operation. And

06:41.920 --> 06:48.760
you offered the full range of courses for 
freshmen.

06:48.740 --> 06:53.760
Did any of them come into the main campus to take any 
courses? Faculty

06:53.740 --> 07:03.960
people, I taught mostly on the main campus, 
actually. Those of us who did carpool. I had a

07:07.340 --> 07:15.860
semester or two when I taught a couple of days at the 
annex. Describe the students and their

07:15.840 --> 07:20.860
capability. Well, I dealt largely with them. I did 
teach freshmen. But

07:27.320 --> 07:41.770
I dealt very largely with them in a sense

07:27.320 --> 07:41.770
of purpose and what they were there for. Do

07:41.750 --> 07:48.420
you remember any anecdotes or examples of that 
purpose? Purpose and determination on their

07:48.400 --> 07:51.420
part? Any

07:51.400 --> 07:59.730
of them ever say anything or do anything that 
illustrated that? I

07:59.710 --> 08:19.420
would

07:59.710 --> 08:19.420
have thought, you know, that they had all the 
military they

07:59.710 --> 08:19.420
wanted. And their academic performance. Were 
there instances when you could sense that the

08:23.400 --> 08:31.660
experience of where they'd been and what they'd 
seen helped them to understand something that you

08:31.640 --> 08:36.660
were trying to teach them? Well,

08:36.640 --> 08:46.710
obviously we knew they were there. What was your 
teaching load? What courses and how many? We

08:51.880 --> 09:08.030
taught 18

08:51.880 --> 09:08.030
hours.

09:08.010 --> 09:14.869
About what was the enrollment per section?

09:17.175 --> 09:19.140
But no big sections? No big sections. And you gave 
them the same kind of assignments and homework

09:23.820 --> 09:30.840
that you would have any other classes? Pretty 
much. What about their attendance? Was it

09:36.742 --> 09:41.740
regular?

09:41.720 --> 09:44.740
Let's go back to the air base. There were many 
hundreds of students out there and almost all of

09:44.720 --> 09:53.530
their activities were out there. I know that's 
when the fish drill team was created and I

09:53.510 --> 09:58.530
understand there was a freshman band. What 
interaction was there between the main campus of

09:58.510 --> 10:06.940
the students and the air base? Much.

10:14.056 --> 10:24.540
I think the sophomores were very unhappy that they 
weren't getting out the freshmen. Was there any

10:24.520 --> 10:27.870
hazing out there? There was hazing out there 
because there were only freshmen. Only freshmen.

10:34.202 --> 10:54.170
Now, about how many of you faculty lived out there?

10:54.150 --> 10:58.060
It must have been 30 or 40 families. There was a 
housing area near the entrance called The Village

10:58.040 --> 11:05.710
and a group lived up there. The rest of us were in the 
Lee Martins and the Staley Crestwells.

11:19.500 --> 11:19.800
C.K.S. sent an advance summoner

11:22.043 --> 11:41.650
and he

11:22.043 --> 11:41.650
said,

11:22.043 --> 11:41.650
I'll take this in. . . . So I had to dig up the other 
end. And you did garden. Did many others garden out

11:50.155 --> 11:52.050
there? Yeah, there were several gardens.

12:04.680 --> 12:06.700
I just wanted to be sure it was turning. . Was there 
any hazing of the freshmen? I don't think so.

12:18.240 --> 12:20.260
Because there were no sophomores. No sophomores 
either. But they were organized in military

12:21.620 --> 12:25.640
fashion. They ate together. together. Not many of 
them had cars. They kidded me on one of the first

12:35.020 --> 12:41.900
meals we had. I said, you know I don't like beans, 
but these are the best beans I ever ate. Black eyed

12:45.880 --> 12:48.345
peas. Never heard of them. So you all dined in the 
old base mess hall. Did you faculty members eat in

12:58.840 --> 13:02.860
the dining hall or did you eat on your own at home? 
Well, I ate in the dining hall until I met most

13:07.050 --> 13:14.570
people. Describe the faculty social life between 
you faculty families that were out there. Well,

13:22.990 --> 13:46.030
there was an article in the paper that the bridge 
club out

13:22.990 --> 13:46.030
there really

13:46.010 --> 13:53.495
had well get together as a group. We got very close. 
And

13:54.920 --> 14:01.420
you said that Dr. Harrington and or John Paul were 
administratively responsible for? Yes, at

14:11.905 --> 14:20.240
different times, Dr. Harrington.

14:20.220 --> 14:24.240
Now did that have, what was the official title of 
that unit?

14:28.586 --> 14:30.276
Was it the Texas A&M? Oh, the whole unit, Texas A&M 
Annex. And you were out there how long? Four, oh I

14:40.890 --> 14:43.578
didn't know it was that long. We moved well three 
actually. Most others

14:50.540 --> 14:52.109
stayed one more year. So then that lasted from 46 to 
50, the interim period between World War II and

15:00.920 --> 15:03.950
Vietnam. I mean, and Korean War. Right. And the 
Korean War. Back to, what was your beginning

15:08.920 --> 15:13.733
faculty salary? I believe it was $2,250. For nine 
months.

15:21.610 --> 15:23.481
Okay, most of us got. Well, but I'm assuming that 
was the base. Yeah, that was nine, yeah. That was

15:28.249 --> 15:31.570
nine months. And you and your wife had two 
daughters at that point. Was there an elementary

15:35.550 --> 15:39.570
school out there for those that were school

15:39.550 --> 15:44.127
age? Well, little country school. Little country 
school.

15:52.867 --> 16:00.918
Yeah.

16:00.978 --> 16:09.530
Came

16:00.978 --> 16:09.530
back crying one day. She showed us her report card. 
My A has it marked black. Everybody else had one. Uh

16:18.840 --> 16:20.190
oh, I was gonna say. She was there, I think, two 
years and then left to Bowie. Alright, as you look

16:25.960 --> 16:30.190
back on it, how did those two years, were those good 
years for her?

16:34.999 --> 16:46.180
Alright,

16:34.999 --> 16:46.180
so you taught out there three years.

16:50.232 --> 16:51.260
Then you moved to this house. And that's 1949. And 
this, what's the address of this house? 208

16:58.095 --> 17:00.270
Fairview Avenue. Okay, describe this, the 
neighborhood when you all moved in. What was

17:04.250 --> 17:06.578
Southside like? Well, it really, it was pretty.

17:13.320 --> 17:18.328
This house was built. You know,

17:20.151 --> 17:31.350
the man in

17:20.151 --> 17:31.350
the extension thought she was going to lose her 
shirt. So they formed a committee to try to, Miss

17:31.330 --> 17:39.050
Jenny went ahead and did alright. Then, I don't 
know much about this, but shortly thereafter,

17:43.030 --> 17:53.370
they formed

17:43.030 --> 17:53.370
what they called the corporation. And they built 
the good money houses.

18:01.536 --> 18:02.700
Were there, were there any native trees? On these 
blocks?

18:10.993 --> 18:12.300
We have a native juju tree. Okay. And this area is, 
am I correct that it was called Southside or

18:17.430 --> 18:21.450
Southgate? College

18:21.430 --> 18:27.228
Park. Oh, okay. Were there some older houses east 
of us, just south of what used to be called Jersey?

18:34.880 --> 18:38.503
Yes.

18:38.523 --> 18:41.200
The, alright, you all move here. The girls grow up 
here, your two daughters. Um, and you then, did you

18:45.180 --> 18:51.200
teach a fourth year out at the air base or did you 
start teaching full time here on the campus that

18:55.180 --> 18:55.723
fourth year? I began teaching full time. About how 
big was the English department in numbers of

19:00.610 --> 19:04.126
faculty?

19:05.975 --> 19:07.180
They had hired a good many, a motley crew. Who were, 
let's let's try to recall as many of those as you

19:19.220 --> 19:23.240
can. Who were some of the senior English faculty 
when you arrived? Well, Dr. Mayo headed the

19:30.920 --> 19:32.670
department. Dr. Morgan was,

19:32.650 --> 19:52.633
Nolan Shepard.

19:52.994 --> 19:58.420
Alright,

19:52.994 --> 19:58.420
let's go back. Louie Hauer. Louie Hauer. Let's go 
back. Describe Dr. Mayo for someone that may never

20:02.400 --> 20:06.570
have met him. Well, he's a very charming man. Very 
lively and articulate and learned and cordial. He

20:18.413 --> 20:19.420
just exuded charm. Couldn't bear a moment of 
silence. Now, he was the department head? Yes, he

20:26.418 --> 20:38.930
had been moved over.

20:38.910 --> 20:42.930
And y'all, the department office in the academic 
building? Which floors? The floors aren't there.

20:50.987 --> 20:51.550
We were just below the architects. Alright, they 
were on the, I think they're the fourth or the

20:55.530 --> 20:57.126
fifth, whatever it is. Yeah, so we were on the floor 
below them, whatever that was. I remember later

20:59.530 --> 21:03.860
when I was working every night trying to write a 
dissertation, my wife would worry about me and I'd

21:03.840 --> 21:08.370
say, go in there and load the office. Never alone. 
The architects were there all night. Let's see.

21:15.293 --> 21:16.059
Dr. Abbott. Describe him. Very

21:17.430 --> 21:20.984
dapper. Very dapper little fellow. I think the 
students called him Jelly Abbott. And he...

21:26.800 --> 21:35.640
Now, he became a dean, didn't he?

21:41.520 --> 21:43.540
Dean of liberal arts, briefly. He spent one year on 
the board. He became an outstanding professor.

21:50.326 --> 21:51.060
What was his specialty? Well,

21:51.040 --> 21:55.800
no strange I don't think he ever thought of it. Oh, 
okay. Let's see. Did Dr. Mayo have a nickname? Did

22:05.649 --> 22:08.780
the students give him a nickname? If he did, I 
didn't. I never knew him. Dr. Morgan. Let's go to

22:11.882 --> 22:12.780
him. Bloody. Bloody Morgan. And he would later be 
department head, wouldn't he? Yes. Describe him.

22:21.256 --> 22:23.350
Well, he was short, stocky, bald-headed, 
dog-mad, pretty much knew it all. Excellent

22:30.960 --> 22:36.780
golfer and played baseball in the league. Had a big 
league tryout, which didn't materialize.

22:50.650 --> 22:52.670
Described himself as a scholar with maybe he said a 
foul manners. Not

22:54.870 --> 23:00.140
many of those senior colleagues were Texans, were 
they?

23:05.574 --> 23:06.220
They all came from from a wide variety of... John 
Paul had

23:10.470 --> 23:18.497
Vanderbilt. Vanderbilt. Hedgecock was at 
Tennessee. Mayo.

23:26.077 --> 23:31.060
Dr. Mayo.

23:31.040 --> 23:33.060
Because in some of the other areas, I know there 
were lots of Aggies, and you started working on

23:35.040 --> 23:39.060
your doctoral degree when?

23:43.400 --> 23:43.823
50. So you took leave? And did you take wife and 
daughters with you? Oh, yes, I did. The housing was

23:52.480 --> 23:56.100
tight. We lived in a trailer, a

23:59.560 --> 24:04.840
field house and a stadium. It was called,

24:13.630 --> 24:14.957
maybe I'll think of it. I can't think what that 
trailer area was called. Something Park, I

24:17.630 --> 24:19.650
believe. Anyhow, we had a trailer with all the 
water in it and bathhouses. Actually, we were

24:30.880 --> 24:32.210
comfortable. They had the thing organized. We 
were all graduate students. They had a body that

24:40.190 --> 24:42.210
took charge of the thing. We had to get permission 
to get a larger trailer and bring our other

24:46.190 --> 24:48.210
daughter. We went up with our younger daughter 
only, leaving our older daughter, Mary Margaret,

24:52.190 --> 24:54.210
in the school in Lexington, Illinois with her 
grandmother. They gave us permission to get a

25:00.190 --> 25:02.210
bigger trailer. We were on the right side of town. 
They went to the best schools in

25:06.190 --> 25:09.640
the city. Mary Margaret to West High School. We'd 
forgotten the elementary school in 32. But they

25:16.388 --> 25:17.640
were on the right side of town. We were actually 
very comfortable. The kids would go down and

25:25.620 --> 25:27.640
Margaret would work to help put me through. She 
worked in Wisconsin General Hospital and she

25:31.620 --> 25:33.640
worked nights as a nurse's aide. I was along with 
the kids. The little girls would go down to take a

25:39.620 --> 25:41.640
shower and hide in stalls and listen to the young 
ladies talk about their babies. We had no woman to

25:47.620 --> 25:49.640
go down and get them out. Did A&M give you a leave of 
absence? Yes. You knew you had a slot coming back.

25:59.900 --> 26:01.072
Yes. You funded all of this entirely yourself. 
Yes. We rented

26:07.900 --> 26:36.980
the house.

26:36.960 --> 26:40.610
You came back then and finished your dissertation 
a little later. Your special area was what? Yes, I

26:49.360 --> 27:06.310
finished all of it.

27:06.290 --> 27:08.310
How many pages did you write? I said I didn't write 
any and they sent me 400. She didn't approve of

27:12.290 --> 27:14.310
that.

27:19.680 --> 27:21.700
During the 50s what were the changes here at A&M? 
During the 50s. What were the changes here at A&M?

27:31.290 --> 27:33.310
The moment goes down a little as the veterans go on. 
One

27:35.290 --> 27:39.670
thing I remember is that at that

27:39.650 --> 27:48.920
time the computers

27:48.900 --> 27:52.930
came along. The punch

27:52.910 --> 28:00.170
cards. The first study done with Charlie

28:02.150 --> 28:08.380
Hagelman who was the head of Lamar. Then Milton 
Hognick did a concordance to a student James By who

28:17.890 --> 28:23.750
is

28:17.890 --> 28:23.750
now a senior engineer with IBM in Phoenix. I 
remember the computers then. That's one thing

28:30.320 --> 28:33.610
that happened. When you all come back the students 
generalize about the students and what their

28:41.050 --> 28:43.070
interests were in the 50s. Were

28:45.050 --> 28:50.520
there many English majors? Were there many social 
sciences, humanities students at A&M then? I

28:57.420 --> 29:00.780
don't know how many majors. The typical student 
taking one of your advanced courses taking it as an

29:05.680 --> 29:07.700
elective? We

29:07.680 --> 29:12.120
had some who did that. Those who did were good 
students. Do you recall any pranks or jokes or

29:22.960 --> 29:26.980
incidents in classes where the students figured 
out some kind of something or other? Anybody ever

29:32.160 --> 29:34.180
pull one off in class on you?

29:42.520 --> 29:44.540
I really don't remember. Your nickname I 
understand was Happy. I think I discovered they

29:50.520 --> 29:52.540
called me Happy Harry. Do you know when you 
discovered that?

29:58.630 --> 30:00.650
I don't know. I don't remember how I found it out. 
Let's stay with these nicknames a little. Mr.

30:04.630 --> 30:05.977
Coffers, D.B. Coffers. Dusty Butt. Dusty Butt. 
Bloody Morgan. Did Huggett have a nickname? If so,

30:15.160 --> 30:17.180
I didn't know it. Any others you remember in 
English or anywhere else? Well,

30:22.180 --> 30:28.480
elsewhere of course where Ruth Jackson

30:34.580 --> 30:38.620
Thompson and Dr. Dan the Grade Point Man. Oh,

30:38.600 --> 30:45.860
Jock Woods. Oh, yes. Now

30:47.889 --> 30:55.200
I anoint you as a philosopher. What did those 
nicknames really mean? Why did students come up

31:02.090 --> 31:04.110
with those? Oh, I think it was affection maybe. I 
agree with you. Maybe

31:12.190 --> 31:20.170
affection may be too strong. I don't know. I think 
it was kind of affection and respect Now, correct

31:24.150 --> 31:26.170
me if I'm wrong. They did not ever intentionally 
use those

